To serve a JSON object instead of a string, you can modify the "hello_world()" function to return a JSON response using the Flask "jsonify" function. Here's an example of how to modify the previous code to serve a JSON object:

```
from flask import Flask, jsonify

app = Flask(name)

@app.route('/')
def hello_world():
data = {
'message': 'Hello, world!'
}
return jsonify(data)

if name == 'main':
app.run()
```

In this updated version of the code, we import the "jsonify" function from Flask and use it to create a JSON response. We define a dictionary called "data" that contains a single key-value pair, where the key is "message" and the value is "Hello, world!".

The "jsonify" function takes a dictionary as its argument and returns a JSON-formatted response with the appropriate content-type headers. When we visit the root URL of our Flask application, we will see a JSON object with the "message" key and its associated value.

You can test this modified script in the same way as the previous example, by opening a web browser and navigating to http://localhost:5000/. This time, you should see a JSON object with the "message" key and its associated value displayed in your browser.

Sure, here is an example of a simple python script that opens an API endpoint and serves a string:
```
from flask import Flask, request, jsonify
import requests
import json
import time

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/greetings', methods=['GET'])
def greetings():
    username = request.args.get('username')
    name = request.args.get('name')
    if username and name:
        message = f"Hello {name}, welcome to my API! Your username is {username}"
    else:
        message = "Hello, world! This is my API."
    payload = {"message": message, "status": "success", "timestamp": time.time()}
    response = jsonify(payload)
    return response

@app.route('/insults', methods=['GET'])
def insults():
    headers = {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json',
        'Accept': 'application/json'
    }
    res = requests.get('https://insults.io/api/insult', headers=headers)
    insult = res.json().get('insult')
    payload = {"message": insult, "status": "success", "timestamp": time.time()}
    response = jsonify(payload)
    return response

@app.route('/random_number', methods=['GET'])
def random_number():
    try:
        min_val = int(request.args.get('min'))
        max_val = int(request.args.get('max'))
    except Exception as e:
        payload = {"message": "Invalid input. Please enter a valid integer value for 'min' and 'max' query parameters.", "status": "error", "timestamp": time.time()}
        response = jsonify(payload)
        return response
    random_num = str(int((time.time() % (max_val - min_val)) + min_val))
    payload = {"message": f"Your random number is {random_num}.", "status": "success", "timestamp": time.time()}
    response = jsonify(payload)
    return response

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True)
```

The error "Uncaught TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'id')" is likely occurring because "req.body.id" is undefined. To resolve this error, you should add a check to verify that "req.body.id" exists before trying to access its properties.

You can do this by adding a conditional statement before accessing "req.body.id":

'''
app.delete('/post', (req, res) => {
    const user = getUser(req.user.user_id);
    if (!user) return res.sendStatus(401);
    if (!req.body.id) return res.sendStatus(400);
    const post = getPost(req.body.id);
    if (!post) return res.sendStatus(404);
    if (post.user_id != req.user.user_id) return res.sendStatus(403);
    // Code that deletes the post through DB
    return res.sendStatus(201);
});
'''

This way, if req.body.id is undefined, the code will return a status of 400 Bad Request instead of attempting to access undefined properties.

